    "organization" : "The Global Alliance for Improved Nutrition (GAIN) is an international organization working toward a world free of malnutrition and its debilitating effects. GAIN runs a variety of programs to support fortification of staple foods to increase global health; the program targeted by The Life You Can Save and by GiveWell is GAIN's Universal Salt Iodization (USI) Program. <br/><br/> Iodine is a micronutrient crucial for bone and brain development. Deficiency of iodine is the worldâ€™s most prevalent cause of preventable brain damage. It can also cause goiter, cretinism, stunting, increased infant mortality, miscarriage and stillbirth. It more deeply entrenches individuals, families and countries in a downward spiral of extreme poverty. <br/><br/> In many countries, sufficient iodine intake is rarely achievable due to a variety of factors including food shortages, limited food diversity, poor soil, and lack of sufficient iodization in staple foods and salt. As a result, iodine deficiency is still prevalent in much of the developing world. An estimated 1.75 billion people, including 25% of households in the developing world, are at risk of iodine deficiency and its serious health complications.  A highly cost-effective way to address this problem is through salt iodization. <br/><br/> GAIN helps salt producers around the globe build their capacity to iodize properly, and helps set up more cost-effective procurement and distribution mechanisms, resulting in reduced iodine prices and better access. GAIN works with governments to build sustainable monitoring and evaluation systems. GAINâ€™s activities include advocacy, technical assistance, supplying equipment, and training. This multi-faceted approach is designed to ensure iodization programs in high-burden countries grow and last far beyond GAINâ€™s involvement, bringing efforts closer to optimal global iodine nutrition.",
    "recommendation" : "GAIN is recommended by rigorous charity evaluator <a href='http://www.givewell.org/international/top-charities/GAIN' target='_blank'>GiveWell <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> as a â€œStandout Charity,â€  and as promising by <a href='https://www.givingwhatwecan.org/blog/2014-12-05/our-recommended-charities-year' target='_blank'>Giving What We Can <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a>. GAIN has partnered and/or received support from respected organizations such as The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, Unicef and USAID.",
    "numbers" : "Salt iodization is safe, relatively easy, and inexpensive, delivering dramatic returns on investment at both individual and national levels. Before widespread salt iodization, <a href='http://www.ign.org/cm_data/2008_Zimmermann_Iodine_requirements_and_the_risk_and_benefits_of_correcting_iodine_def_in_populations_JTEMB.pdf' target='_blank'>yearly potential losses</a> attributable to iodine deficiency in the developing world have been estimated as $35.7 billion. Annual salt iodization runs an estimated $0.5 billion â€” providing a 70 to 1 benefit to cost ratio. And according to the Copenhagen Consensus, correcting iodine deficiency yields benefits in increased future cognitive ability with an estimated <a href='http://www.copenhagenconsensus.com/sites/default/files/bpp_fortification.pdf' target='_blank'>30:1 benefit:cost ratio</a>. <br/><br/> Countries throughout the world have varying rates of Universal Salt Iodization (USI) coverage, and many different organizations work together to increase this coverage worldwide, so it is difficult to disentangle the costs and impact of each organization. GAIN estimates it has expanded access to adequately iodized salt at costs ranging from $0.05 per person in India to $0.18 per person in Bangladesh; they judge the direct cost on average for their roles in providing a lifetime of adequately iodized salt to one additional person not previously protected from iodine deficiency as $0.20.  This includes the capital costs of equipment, initial training, lab infrastructure, and the establishment of cost-recovery systems.  It is a conservative estimate based on the <a href='http://www.the-chiefexecutive.com/contractors/supply-chain/gain/' target='_blank'>200 million <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> additional people who have gained access to iodized salt in countries where GAIN has worked since 2008, as a result of their investment of $20 million (leveraging their partnersâ€™ investments). Because GAIN works on supply-side inputs, it is likely safe to say that the the organization has played a vital role in the expansion of USI coverage for more than 200 million individuals. GAINâ€™s organizational overhead is around 10%, and has already been included in these cost efficiency estimates.  Keep in mind that <a href='http://overheadmyth.com/faqs/' target='_blank'>overhead ratio <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> is not a direct reflection of charity effectiveness.",
