    "organization" : "The World Health Organization says that â€œIodine deficiency is the worldâ€™s most prevalent, yet easily preventable, cause of brain damage.â€  Iodine deficiency can lead to lower intelligence, poor educability, goiter, hypothyroidism, mental retardation, cretinism, poor growth, stunting, increased infant mortality, miscarriages and stillbirths.  The Iodine Global Network (IGN) is a leader in the fight to sustainably eliminate iodine deficiency and its disastrous effects worldwide. Benefits of iodized salt include improved health, lowered public health care costs, economic growth, and reduction of poverty. To support Universal Salt Iodization (USI), the IGN advocates for national salt iodization programs, tracks iodization progress, provides guidance on related programmatic and scientific issues, serves as liaison between various stakeholder groups, and helps sustain and improve the quality of existing programs. <br/><br/> Countries have varying rates of USI coverage, and many different organizations work together to increase coverage worldwide, so it is difficult to disentangle the costs and impact of each organization. IGN works in direct support of national USI coalitions, advocating and extending scientific and technical guidance through Regional and National Coordinators.",
    "recommendation" : "IGN was formed in 2012 by a merger of two organizations: The International Council for Control of Iodine Deficiency Disorders â€“ a partner of UNICEF, WHO, and national governments, among others â€“ and The Network for Sustained Elimination of Iodine Deficiency, a global coalition of public, private, international and civic organizations, all supporting iodization of salt.  This intervention is recognized as a top development investment by both the World Bank and the Copenhagen Consensus, and is consistent with six of the Millennium Development Goals. IGN is recommended as a â€œStandout Charityâ€ by rigorous evaluator <a href='http://www.givewell.org/international/top-charities/IGN' target='_blank'>GiveWell <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> and as promising by <a href='https://www.givingwhatwecan.org/blog/2014-12-05/our-recommended-charities-year' target='_blank'>Giving What We Can <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a>.",
    "numbers" : "Eradication of iodine deficiency is highly <a href='http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK11761/' target='_blank'>cost-effective <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a>â€”worldwide, the cost of salt iodization per year is estimated at $0.02-0.05 per child covered; the cost per child's death averted is $1000 and per disability-adjusted life year gained is $34-36.  Iodization also saves substantial health costs. Before widespread salt iodization, <a href='http://www.ign.org/cm_data/2008_Zimmermann_Iodine_requirements_and_the_risk_and_benefits_of_correcting_iodine_def_in_populations_JTEMB.pdf' target='_blank'>yearly potential losses</a> attributable to iodine deficiency in the developing world have been estimated as $35.7 billion. Annual salt iodization runs an estimated $0.5 billion â€” providing a 70 to 1 benefit to cost ratio. And according to the Copenhagen Consensus, correcting iodine deficiency yields benefits in terms of increased future cognitive ability with an estimated <a href='http://www.copenhagenconsensus.com/sites/default/files/bpp_fortification.pdf' target='_blank'>30:1 benefit:cost ratio</a>. <br/><br/> IGN reported to The Life You Can Save that in a population of 10,000,000 with 70% coverage, their annual costs of supporting efforts to sustain protection of the 7 million covered individuals are $70,000 (or $0.01 per person per year).  IGN also reinforces GAINâ€™s (another of our recommended charities) work to expand coverage through such efforts as advocacy, coalition building, and revision and expansion of existing legislation and iodine standards as salt consumption patterns change.  IGN estimates their direct expansion support costs to average $0.05 per person (thus, working in concert with GAIN and other implementation agencies, in the same 10M person population with 70% coverage, the IGN could support expansion to 3 million additional people with an investment of $150K).  IGNâ€™s overhead is 10.1% and has already been included in its cost efficiency estimates.  Keep in mind that the <a href='http://overheadmyth.com/faqs/' target='_blank'>overhead ratio <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> is not a direct reflection of charity effectiveness.",
