    "organization" : "In Africa, there are only 2.3 healthcare workers for every 1000 people.  And in rural areas, there are no product chains or franchises to bring essential health goods to populations who lack the means to reach or afford such products.  Living Goods (LG) trains saleswomen, called Community Health Promoters (CHPs), to address this problem. <br/><br/> New saleswomen go through 2-3 weeks of introductory training and monthly follow-ups in basic health care, including preventive measures and how to diagnose and cure the most common diseases like malaria, childhood pneumonia, and diarrhea. Part of their job is to educate customers and communities in effective usage. LG provides the CHPs with initial supplies like uniforms, storage containers, and thermometers as well as with start-up inventory, bought with a low-interest loan. This includes a range of important health products, e.g. anti-malarial bednets, deworming pills, clean-water filters, treatments for malaria and diarrhea, kits for clean delivery of babies, and fortified foods, as well as everyday products such as soap, sanitary pads, condoms, solar-powered lamps and cellphone chargers. <br/><br/> The dual goal is to significantly improve community health, including reducing child mortality by at least 15%, while also providing saleswomen with the chance to earn a living.",
