    "numbers" : "At the end of 2015, Living Goods (LG) had 140 branches, employing over 3,908 Community Health Promoters. Their plan for the next 4 years is to grow to over 9,7000 franchised agents supporting 7.6 million of the poor in a number of countries. Living Goods has supported 339,753 pregnancies, treated 1,184,760 children under 5 for deadly diseases, and sold over 62,000 clean-burning cookstoves (among many other improvement products).<br/><br/> Researchers from the world-respected Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab (J-PAL) are performing <a href='http://livinggoods.org/what-we-do/measuring-impact/' target='_blank'>Randomized Controlled Trials <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> (RCT) â€”widely recognized as an optimal evaluation toolâ€”to monitor and inform LGâ€™s progress towards the objective of significantly reducing under-5 child mortality. LG is also using randomized follow-up customer calls to improve quality control and monitoring. Living Goods tracks the performance of key health metrics (e.g. treatments by disease and age, pregnancies supported, and post-natal follow-ups) as well as sales and profitability.<br/><br/>Our calculatorâ€™s figures are based only on data from Living Goodsâ€™ Uganda program because LGâ€™s 2011-2013 Randomized Controlled Trial focused on its Uganda program, and because Living Goodsâ€™ Kenya program is undergoing an overhaul to better reflect the successful structure of its Uganda program. Living Goods projects a net annual cost per Ugandan Community Health Promoter of roughly $1509.68 and a net cost per Ugandan served of $1.89 in 2016, including overhead.  LGâ€™s 2015-2019 Financial Model Forecast projects a net cost per Community Health Promoter of roughly $1137 and a net cost per person served of $1.45 over the next four years. <br/><br/>\nUsing data from J-PALâ€™s RCT and the 2012 <a href='http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SH.DYN.MORT' target='_blank'>World Bank Open Data World Development Indicator <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a>, Living Goods has estimated the cost per life saved in their Uganda scale-up plan at $3500 over the next 4 years. Charity evaluator GiveWell has <a href='http://www.givewell.org/international/top-charities/living-goods#OuradjustmentstoLivingGoodsestimates' target='_blank'>made the estimate <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> that between 2014 and 2016, LGâ€™s cost per life saved will average around $10,000.  This number is significantly higher due to GiveWellâ€™s inclusion of Living Goodâ€™s Kenya program costs in their analysis and GiveWellâ€™s more conservative assumptions concerning factors including the Uganda programâ€™s replicability and the impact of unrelated factors simultaneously decreasing Ugandaâ€™s Under-5 mortality rate.  Living Goodsâ€™ expected 2016 overhead is about 7% (keep in mind that the <a href='http://overheadmyth.com/faqs/' target='_blank'>overhead ratio <span class='ExternalLinkDrk'></span></a> is not a direct measurement of charity effectiveness).  The overhead has already been factored into our Impact Calculator price points.",
