    "organization" : "Smallholder farmers make up <a href='http://www.ifad.org/rpr2011/report/e/rpr2011.pdf' target='_blank'>70%</a> of the worldâ€™s poor; in Asia and sub-Saharan Africa, they provide up to <a href='https://hiu.state.gov/Products/13909_WorldFood_LandscapeUNCLASS.pdf' target='_blank'>80%</a> of the food supply. Yet most of these farmers live in remote areas where they lack access to basic agricultural supplies and training. Many cannot manage to grow enough food to feed their families, much less make a profit to allow for necessities year-round. A yearly â€œhunger seasonâ€ is commonplace. As populations grow, the problem is exacerbated.<br /><br />One Acre Fund has developed a service bundle that enables smallholder farmers to significantly increase farm production as well as income, with the potential to grow their way out of hunger and extreme poverty. The bundle includes naturally improved hybrid seeds and fertilizer, financing for farm inputs, agricultural training, and market facilitation to maximize profits. Farmers are taught sustainable practices to minimize harvest loss with proper storage techniques and maximize profits from harvest sales. The organization continually updates its services based on farmer feedback. One Acre Fund also creates career opportunities, as many of those on One Acre Fundâ€™s staff began as client farmers.",
    "recommendation" : "One Acre Fund is one of <a href='http://www.thelifeyoucansave.org/where-to-donate' target='_blank'>The Life You Can Saveâ€™s top-rated charities</a>. But don't just take our word for it. In 2010, the organization was one of five to receive the <a href='http://skoll.org/organization/one-acre-fund/' target='_blank'>Skoll Award for Social Entrepreneurship</a>. In 2013, The Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation and One Acre Fund launched an $11.6 million <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/about-us/press-and-awards#sec-16_321_2_1' target='_blank'>partnership</a> to increase access to innovative agriculture technologies and foster partnerships with African governments. In 2015, the Swiss nonprofit Global Geneva named One Acre Fund #15 on its list of the <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/blogs/information/post/global-journal-rank-one-acre-fund-in-top-500-ngos/980' target='_blank'>worldâ€™s best NGOs</a> and Fast Company Magazine named One Acre Fund one of the <a href='http://www.fastcompany.com/3041821/most-innovative-companies-2015/the-worlds-top-10-most-innovative-companies-of-2015-in-africa' target='_blank'>ten most innovative companies in Africa</a>. Read more about the organizationâ€™s accolades <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/about-us/press-and-awards' target='_blank'>here</a>.",
    "numbers" : "One Acre Fund served more than 500,000 farm families in East Africa in 2017.  They are on track to reach 1 million farm households by 2020.  In 2016, program participant farmers saw an average increase of <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/results/impact' target='_blank'>$100 in additional profits</a>, representing a 50% gain in farm income from supported activities. The core program is growing in large part due to One Acre Fundâ€™s revenue model, in which farmers are given a loan of about $75 (including a ~17% interest/service fee) to cover most of the cost of their â€œfull service bundleâ€ including seed, fertilizer, and training. Farmers repay their loans as income is made during or after harvest. In 2016,  <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/results/impact' target='_blank'>98%</a> of farmers will repaid their loans, covering <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/results/impact#sec-968_441_6_5' target='_blank'>73%</a> of field program costs. Donations and grants are needed to fill the remaining gap between field revenues and field expenses of roughly $33 per farmer (including overhead).<br><br>The organizationâ€™s impact on farmer profits is calculated by comparing the profits of One Acre Fund clients to highly similar comparison group farmers. Because One Acre Fund is unable to capture reliable profit data from economic activities outside their program, they measure profit impact only on supported activities. Supported activities include farming of crops supported by One Acre Fund (subsistence crops like maize, beans, and millet, but not cash crops like tobacco and sugar). Supported activities also include non-farm â€œadd-onâ€ products (details below). For more information about the activities One Acre Fund measures, see the organizationâ€™s <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/results/impact#sec-968_438_3_2' target='_blank'>impact page</a>.<br><br>One Acre Fund <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/blogs/information/post/not-an-oxymoron-financial-sustainability-for-non-profit-social-enterprise/928' target='_blank'>strives to achieve core program financial sustainability</a> in order to operate and grow efficiently while freeing donor dollars to fund research and policy advocacy efforts. The organization performs extensive research and testing of new products, systems and strategies designed to make smallholder farmers more prosperous.  Innovative â€œadd-onâ€ products like solar lights and higher-efficiency cookstoves result from this work, further improving farm familiesâ€™ quality of life and contributing to increased profits.  One Acre Fund simultaneously engages African governments, microfinance organizations and other key agriculture actors in dialogue to shape policy decisions that strengthen agricultural ecosystems, more effectively provide rural finance, and communicate information to the greater public.<br><br>According to <a href='http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=13262' target='_blank'>Charity Navigator</a>, in 2014 One Acre Fund spent 90.4% of its budget on program expenses, with 6.5% spent on administration and 3.1% on fundraising. Keep in mind that the overhead ratio is not a direct measurement of charity effectiveness.  See One Acre Fundâ€™s annual <a href='https://www.oneacrefund.org/results/the-reports' target='_blank'>performance and financial reports</a> for more details on current and long-term impact.",
